### 1. Type Assertions

Type assertions allow you to explicitly tell the compiler what the type of a value is, even if the compiler cannot infer it correctly.

```typescript
let value: any = "hello";

// Explicitly assert the type
let strValue: string = value as string;

console.log(strValue.toUpperCase()); // TypeScript knows this is a string now
```

### 2. Conditional Types

Conditional types can be used to narrow down the type based on runtime checks. This is useful when you want to conditionally set the type based on a known property or value.

```typescript
